<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p>The Hirshfeld surface is a three-dimensional isosurface effectively determining the volume of the molecule in the crystal. The surface itself is defined so that for each point on this surface, one-half of the electron density is due to the spherically averaged noninteracting atoms comprising the molecule, and the other half is due to those comprising the rest of the crystal [
 <xref rid="B66-molecules-24-04387" ref-type="bibr">66</xref>]. The quantity which is mapped onto the surface is 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm97">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>d</mi>
     <mi>norm</mi>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (normalized contact distance), which is the negative or positive sum of 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm98">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>d</mi>
     <mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm99">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>d</mi>
     <mi mathvariant="normal">e</mi>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> when the contacts are shorter or longer than the sum of the van der Waals radii of the interacting atoms, respectively:
 <disp-formula id="FD2-molecules-24-04387">
  <label>(2)</label>
  <math id="mm100">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>d</mi>
      <mi>norm</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mo>(</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi>
       </msub>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <msubsup>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi>
        <mi>vdW</mi>
       </msubsup>
       <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <msubsup>
       <mi>r</mi>
       <mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi>
       <mi>vdW</mi>
      </msubsup>
     </mfrac>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mo>(</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">e</mi>
       </msub>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <msubsup>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal">e</mi>
        <mi>vdW</mi>
       </msubsup>
       <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <msubsup>
       <mi>r</mi>
       <mi mathvariant="normal">e</mi>
       <mi>vdW</mi>
      </msubsup>
     </mfrac>
     <mo>.</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
